The assembly process on this cake is very disappointing. Make sure that your glaze is "chilled" and not just room temperature or cool. In preparing this dessert as written, it became a complete disaster as the glaze and whipped cream oozed out between the layers. I was able to correct by placing cake in freezer to quickly set the glaze. I doubled the glaze recipe from the start, therefore had enough to correct any imperfections. I always refer to epicurious for my baking as I bake desserts for a local restaurant. Usually the desserts that I choose have a 4 fork rating and have always proved to be successful, except for this one.

Rating: 4
This is a delicious and beautiful looking cake. Everyone at my party thought it was great. I made one change which was to use all four layers of cake. I cut the cakes in half and then put them in the freezer for a few hours. That made them very easy to handle. I used 2 1/2 cups of cream, 1/3 cup powdered sugar and 14 oz bag of frozen raspberries. I also folded in two teaspoons of gelatin that had been softened in 1/4 cup of water. Next time I will set aside 2 cups plain whipped cream so I can do some decorative piping. I only had 12 oz of semi-sweet chocolate so I did not increase the ganache. I made thinner layers of ganache on the cake but still ran out on the side. Next time I will use a pound of chocolate and adjust the other ingredients accordingly. The four layers looked very impressive and decadent so don't throw out that last layer. One last thing. I expected this cake to be very heavy but with the cream and raspberries it wasn't.

