I've never understood recipes that tell you to make too much cake for the recipe. Rather than throw half a layer out, I put the batter in three pans, and baked them for half the time the recipe called for. I agree with a few of the other reviewers who said the cake was on the dry side, so if I make it again, I'll cut down on the baking time even more. Maybe because I used all the cake, I found there was not enough glaze, or at least not enuf to put on a thin layer, let it harden and then add a final layer. I was really short, so think I would have been even with 3 layers. And I used frozen raspberries left from our summer harvest. I'm sure fresh would be more attractive. And I used plain yogurt, instead of buttermilk. Anyway, I didn't think it was any more complex or time consuming as any other scratch recipe. I served this for a large gathering, but no one fell over themselves over it. I actually like another chocolate cake recipe from this web site better- old fashioned chocolate cake with fudge frosting- much moister and chocolatey.

