I made this for 24 by increasing cake ingredients by 50%, using an 11*17 pan to make 3 layers (one at a time was no problem). I doubled the glaze and cream filling, and had just enough. Glazing the sides was easier using a warm spatula to soften the glaze a bit. Everyone loved it.

Rating: 4
The recipe makes this more complicated than need be. Instead of making 2 layers, cutting them and throwing one away, I multiplied the cake measurements by 3/4, and baked 3 layers (rotating them top-bottom or bottom-top rack after 10 minutes). I used 8 1/4" pans, and the cakes were done in about 20 minutes. Since you have to remove the cakes before completely cool, I found that the cheap, disposable pans worked much better than the expensive, non-stick variety! If you don't put the eau de vie in the filling, I'd definitely finish it with some fresh berries. I had trouble finding eau-de-vie... I don't know why you couldn't use Chambord, as long as you don't mind coloring the filling pink. Glazing the sides was a pain... I ended up with lots of extra, which I just spread on the top. The end result was rich, yet surprisingly light. A huge hit!

